===== research/e4-paper-section-draft.md =====
   1: # E4 — draft paper section (EN; ES mirror on integration) — v2 anchored-scenario framing — DRAFT
   2: 
   3: > Rewritten to the author's anchored framing — four declared scenarios plus one diagnostic contrast. Resolves the
   4: > rev-paper blockers: (1) reconciles with the paper's own symmetry-gate NO-GO (Δ≈0.025) instead of contradicting it;
   5: > (2) reports the actual numbers.
   6: > Source of numbers: `npm run e4:scenarios | e4:frontier | e4:evidence`; anchors in `research/e4-plausible-anchors.md`.
   7: > Framed as a comparative-institutions robustness result with anchored scenarios + a benchmark theorem, NOT a multiplier.
   8: 
   9: ## E4. When does coverage-routed selection beat central-proxy selection?
  10: 
  11: **Question.** At an equal budget and the same candidate projects, does coverage-routed distributed appraisal (Core
  12: v0) deliver more true social value than a competent central-proxy appraisal — and under exactly what conditions does
  13: each win? We answer with a mechanism model, a stylized benchmark theorem, and four **source-motivated declared scenarios** (plus one diagnostic contrast) that level
  14: the field for both institutions.
  15: 
  16: **Mechanism.** True value splits into support and harm, `S = S⁺ − H` (mean scale). The central planner reads
  17: visible/salient value but is **myopic to harm, salience-gated**: harm-detection `b_H^C·s(V)` rises with a project's
  18: visibility `V`, so on the **low-visibility long tail** — the mass of public projects — it is nearly blind to
  19: concentrated opposition (oversight, opposition, comptroller reach mainly the visible, contested few). The
  20: distributed arm registers harm at weight `(1−β)` across the whole distribution. Under the declared salience-gating
  21: proxy (agenda-setting/salience — the load-bearing and least-empirically-pinned assumption), the aggregate advantage
  22: comes from the long tail: the projects that have no anti-value voice in the status quo.
  23: 
  24: **Model (matched budget; selection only).** `M^C = a + b·S⁺ + w·(v_{p,j}−S⁺) − b_H^C·s(V)·H + η` (project-varying
  25: `v_{p,j}` identifies `w`; form informed by elite-misperception evidence with an explicit political-opinion→project-
  26: value transport gap). The distributed estimate is a baseline-expanded, MNAR-biased mean of citizen reports. Both
  27: arms fund greedily under a shared budget; delivered value is scored on true `S`. Administrative-cost savings and
  28: corruption/leakage are separate, additive channels, deliberately excluded here.
  29: 
  30: **Stylized benchmark theorem.** Under joint normality and fixed-threshold selection, expected selected value per
  31: candidate is `V_k = q·μ_S + φ(z_q)·Cov(S,X_k)/sd(X_k)`, so parity ⇔ `Cov(S,X_D)/sd(X_D) = Cov(S,X_C)/sd(X_C)` (the
  32: intercept `a` is absent). This is a **stylized Gaussian fixed-threshold benchmark** (verified against simulation
  33: within ~0.2 Monte-Carlo SE); it nests the production harm-gated signal only under extra coefficient/gate
  34: restrictions, so it is a sanity-check limit, **not** a proof about the full engine (eligibility, heterogeneous
  35: costs, MNAR, credit) — which is the object.
  36: 
  37: **Four declared scenarios + one diagnostic contrast (level the field both ways).** The four substantive scenarios are
  38: PRO-CENTRAL, NO-MYOPIA (bundle), PROBABLE, PRO-DISTRIBUTED; "Harm-myopia only" is a **diagnostic contrast**, not a
  39: declared scenario. Each knob's reference value is motivated empirically (public-
  40: procurement value is heavy-tailed — Skuhrovec et al. 2013, >40k Czech procurements, Zipf/Pareto — so most projects are
  41: low-visibility; participatory-budgeting turnout ≈1–3% informs participation as a joint moment), theoretically
  42: (agenda-setting/salience for harm myopia), or proxy-informed with a stated, **not-yet-propagated** transport gap
  43: (projection/bias). We are explicit that most magnitudes are declared reference/stress points, not target-domain
  44: calibrated bands (the CIs cover inner Monte-Carlo variability only). Reporting `m = D/O − C/O` (signed fraction of the
  45: full-information greedy benchmark, parity at 0) and each arm's delivered level `D/O`, `C/O`:
  46: 
  47: | scenario (assumptions) | m ± 95% CI | Core v0 | central | winner |
  48: |---|---|---|---|---|
  49: | **Central's declared full-favourable endpoint** — low participation + competent, harm-aware, precise central (some knobs sit outside the registered expectable bands) | **−29.5%** [−29.9, −29.1] | 68% | 98% | **central** |
  50: | **No-myopia bundle** — probable + harm sight + unbiased + precise + no credit (NOT a myopia isolation) | **+6.1%** [5.8, 6.4] | 91% | 85% | ≈ parity |
  51: | **Harm-myopia only** (diagnostic contrast, not a scenario) — probable, changing ONLY the two harm-gate coordinates | **+30.4%** [29.9, 31.0] | 91% | 61% | Core v0 |
  52: | **Probable** — source-motivated reference | **+46.6%** [46.0, 47.4] | 91% | 45% | Core v0 |
  53: | **Distributed's favourable case** | **+199.8%** [197, 202] | 96% | −104% | Core v0 |
  54: 
  55: The field is genuinely level: **the central has a real winning region** — at its declared full-favourable endpoint
  56: (low citizen participation and a competent, harm-aware central) it wins ~30% and delivers 98% of the benchmark. Core
  57: v0 wins under the probable reference. The `D/O`/`C/O` split shows why: the central's delivered level swings
  58: 45%→85%→98% (and −104% when myopic on harmful projects), depending on whether it sees the anti-value and on
  59: participation. The scenarios are declared reference/stress points, not a jointly-calibrated probability region.
  60: 
  61: **Reconciliation with the symmetry-gate NO-GO.** A pre-registered symmetry gate elsewhere reports a small pooled
  62: advantage (Δ≈0.025, below its rebuild threshold). That test **deliberately equips the central with competent,
  63: harm-aware appraisal** — the **no-myopia bundle** row above (+6.1%, same near-parity regime). Attribution is a
  64: **sequential, path-dependent** decomposition (the model is nonlinear): turning off harm-myopia **alone** (only the
  65: two harm-gate coordinates) reduces the probable gap +46.6% → +30.4%, i.e. **16.2 of the 40.5-point decline to +6.1%
  66: (~40%)**; the further step to the full no-myopia bundle (unbiasedness, precision, no credit distortion — which the
  67: gate also assumes) reduces it **24.3 points (~60%)**. So harm-myopia is a **large part but not the majority** of the
  68: collapse. The two results are the same phenomenon under opposite assumptions — a **qualitative reconciliation
  69: hypothesis** (different DGPs), not a reproduced limit.
  70: 
  71: **Where the frontier is.** Across five prespecified one-factor slices (`s_exp, b_H_C, p, beta, a_V`), none flips the
  72: winner from the probable scenario within its plotted range (a limited robustness statement over those five slices,
  73: not all parameters). Interpolating the full set of conditions from probable toward the declared central-favourable
  74: endpoint, the parity frontier is at **t ≈ 0.57** — reached **within the declared interpolation segment**. Which side
  75: a real setting falls on depends on where a measured target configuration would lie between the declared scenarios;
  76: `t` is an illustrative linear mix, not a calibrated competence scale.
  77: 
  78: **Honest limits.** (1) Central magnitudes are proxy-informed, not target-identified: the political-opinion→project-
  79: value transport is an assumption; only target-domain bridge data (planner forecasts, citizen value distributions)
  80: could shrink it. (2) The harm-myopia strength (`s_exp, b_H^C`) is theory-anchored (agenda-setting), the least
  81: empirically pinned knob and the crux. (3) `m>100%`/negative reflect legitimate value destruction (the losing arm
  82: funds net-harmful projects), read via `D/O`, `C/O`. (4) Cost and leakage channels are separate legs. E4 is a
  83: comparative-institutions robustness result with anchored scenarios + a benchmark theorem + a measurement plan —
  84: not an impact estimate.
  85: 
  86: ## Integration checklist (EN + ES, keep 13/13 parity)
  87: - Replace the E4 subsection of `drafts/paper.md`; mirror in `drafts/paper.es.md`.
  88: - Add citations: Skuhrovec et al. 2013 (arXiv:1309.0218); PB turnout (Brennan Center); Broockman–Skovron 2018;
  89:   Gagnon-Bartsch; Dias–Lucas–Sheffer 2025; Prelec et al. 2017; prior-art (Böttcher–Klingebiel 2024; Rey–Endriss 2024;
  90:   Boehmer et al. 2023; Liesiö et al. 2007; Mollick–Nanda 2016).
  91: - Reproducibility appendix: `npm run e4:controls | e4:test | e4:theorem | e4:scenarios | e4:frontier | e4:evidence`
  92:   + the contract hash.
  93: - Keep the embargo: no `×`, no `D/C`, parity at 0, sign + magnitude separated, D/O·C/O for interpretation.
===== research/e4-parity-theorem.md =====
   1: # E4 analytic benchmark — the joint-normal fixed-threshold parity theorem
   2: 
   3: > A **stylized no-myopia Gaussian benchmark**, not a reduction of the full engine. The production engine adds
   4: > eligibility gates, heterogeneous costs, greedy residual fill, MNAR reports, z-scoring, credit, AND a salience-gated
   5: > harm term; this theorem nests it ONLY under the extra restrictions in **Honest scope** below (no harm gate, net
   6: > `S`). It is a sanity-check limit, not a proof about the production engine. Regression:
   7: > `scripts/simulation/e4-v5/theorem-check.mjs` (matches within ~0.2 Monte-Carlo SE). Replaces the retired `β = 1−η`
   8: > harm-weight law (which does not nest the v1.14 model).
   9: 
  10: ## Setup
  11: Candidate projects are i.i.d. draws of `(S, X)`, where `S` is true (mean-scale) value and `X` is a selector's
  12: signal (the central estimate `X_C = M^C`, or the distributed estimate `X_D = M^D`). Assume:
  13: 1. `(S, X)` is **jointly normal**, `Var(X) > 0`.
  14: 2. Equal costs, no eligibility gate, no credit; each selector funds the top fraction `q ∈ (0,1)` by its own `X`.
  15: 3. Selection is at the **population threshold** `t = μ_X + σ_X · z_q`, `z_q = Φ⁻¹(1−q)` (equivalently, the exact
  16:    top-`qK` quota in the `K → ∞` limit).
  17: 
  18: ## Lemma (expected selected value per candidate)
  19: ```
  20: V := E[S · 1{X > t}] = q·μ_S + φ(z_q) · Cov(S,X)/σ_X ,
  21: ```
  22: where `φ` is the standard normal pdf.
  23: 
  24: **Proof.** Joint normality gives the linear conditional mean `E[S | X = x] = μ_S + (Cov(S,X)/σ_X²)(x − μ_X)`. Then
  25: ```
  26: E[S·1{X>t}] = ∫_t^∞ E[S|X=x] f_X(x) dx
  27:             = μ_S·P(X>t) + (Cov(S,X)/σ_X²)·∫_t^∞ (x − μ_X) f_X(x) dx.
  28: ```
  29: `P(X>t) = q`, and the standard truncated-normal identity `∫_t^∞ (x − μ_X) f_X(x) dx = σ_X·φ(z_q)` give
  30: `V = q·μ_S + (Cov(S,X)/σ_X²)·σ_X·φ(z_q) = q·μ_S + φ(z_q)·Cov(S,X)/σ_X`. ∎
  31: 
  32: ## Parity condition
  33: For two selectors `X_C`, `X_D` at the same `q`, the common `q·μ_S` term and the common positive tail factor
  34: `φ(z_q)` cancel, so
  35: ```
  36: V_D = V_C   ⇔   Cov(S,X_D)/σ_{X_D} = Cov(S,X_C)/σ_{X_C}.
  37: ```
  38: **The parity boundary is the equality of the two signal-to-noise covariance ratios `Cov(S,X_k)/sd(X_k)`.** The
  39: intercept `a` of the central model is **absent** (rank-invariant under a fixed funded share with no gate); it
  40: re-enters only in the numerical model through the own-estimate eligibility gate and heterogeneous `/c_j`.
  41: 
  42: For the central signal `X_C = a + (b−w)·S + w·v_p + η` with a distinct project-varying projection `Z = v_p − S`
  43: (typed as its own variable, `η ⊥ (S, v_p)`):
  44: ```
  45: Cov(S,X_C) = b·Var(S) + w·Cov(S,Z),
  46: Var(X_C)   = b²·Var(S) + w²·Var(Z) + 2bw·Cov(S,Z) + Var(η).
  47: ```
  48: 
  49: ## Large-K corollary (link to the frozen estimand)
  50: The lemma is about expected selected sums, not automatically the frozen ratio-of-sums estimand. If
  51: `O_K/K → V_O > 0` (oracle LLN), the numerators `D_K/K, C_K/K` converge, and `Pr(O_K ≤ o_min) → 0`, then
  52: ```
  53: m_K = Σ(D_K − C_K)/Σ O_K  →  (V_D − V_C)/V_O ,
  54: ```
  55: so the covariance-ratio equality is the parity boundary **in the large-project limit**. Finite-world `m` is
  56: numerical; the engine's ratio-of-sums estimator is the finite-`K` object the lemma approximates.
  57: 
  58: ## Honest scope
  59: - **The production central signal is NOT this benchmark's `X_C` without extra restrictions.** The engine's central
  60:   estimate is `M^C = a + b·S⁺ + w·(v_{p,j}−S⁺) − b_H^C·s(V)·H + η` (support `S⁺`, minus a **visibility-gated harm**
  61:   term). The benchmark's `X_C = a + (b−w)S + w·v_p + η` uses **net** `S = S⁺ − H` with no separate harm term. Matching
  62:   them requires `−b_H^C·s(V)·H = −(b−w)·H`, i.e. the **coefficient condition `b_H^C·s(V) = b−w`** (a constant gate at
  63:   exactly that value) — OR the trivial `H ≡ 0`. A constant gate ALONE is insufficient. So the benchmark literally
  64:   nests the production signal only in that special case; otherwise it is a **modified net-`S`, no-separate-harm
  65:   stylized model** — a sanity-check Gaussian benchmark, NOT a proof that the full harm-gated engine reduces to it.
  66: - The MNAR distributed signal is **not** exactly jointly normal at finite reach (thresholded non-response +
  67:   Bernoulli thinning); the Gaussian mapping is a **moment-matched reduced-form approximation**, not an identity.
  68:   So this lemma is the analytic sanity check, and the numerical frontier (with the true DGP) is the object.
  69: - `a` is deliberately absent from the benchmark frontier; do not read a benchmark magnitude off `a`.

